explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro is used directly on both parameters. To prove the parameter variables themselves are not modified you must inspect the macro expansion/definition (it could conceivably assign to or rebind the parameter name, do a cast, or perform other side-effects).

OS_ObjectIdFindByName: This is the only non-macro call in the function that takes both parameters. You need its prototype/definition to determine whether it is a real function (pass-by-value of the pointer, allowed to modify *sock_id but not caller's sock_id variable) or a macro/inline implementation that might reference or reassign the caller parameter identifier.

osal_id_t: The typedef of osal_id_t is required to understand what sock_id points to (an integer type vs a pointer type). If osal_id_t is itself a pointer type, semantics change and the analysis of whether the function modifies the parameter (the pointer variable) vs the object referred to requires this.

LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The constant/macro passed to OS_ObjectIdFindByName could indicate a macro-based implementation or conditional compilation path; include its definition to fully inspect any macro expansions or side-effects related to the call site.

UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: The static call graph shows UT test-stub wrappers around calls. Those stubs/macros can be injected around the call sites (or expand in-place) and potentially capture or modify parameter identifiers. To be sure the original parameter variables are not modified you must inspect these test-stub/handler definitions that may wrap OS_ObjectIdFindByName or OS_CHECK_POINTER in the build being analyzed.
